Wiltshire, England":"Wiltshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Gloucestershire, England":"Gloucestershire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"about 1120–before 1205":"about 1120–before 1205","1120–1205":"1120–1205","1121–1205":"1121–1205","1141–Male":"1141–Deceased","1098–Male":"1098–Deceased","1100–Female":"1100–Deceased","Abt 1141":"about 1141","before 1205":"before 1205","1205":"1205","1100":"1100","1121":"1121","1098":"1098","1120":"1120","1141":"1141","about 1120":"about 1120","Immersmere, Wiltshire, England":"Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom","Gloucestershire, England":"Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Franc","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["French and Catalan: from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Franko</i>, in origin an ethnic name for a Frank, which also came to be used as an adjective meaning ‘free, open-hearted, generous’ (Old French <i>franc</i> ‘free’, i.e. not a serf or slave); see   Frank   2. Compare French   Franck   2.","Polish, Czech, and Slovak: from a Slavicized form of the German personal name   Franz  .","Slovenian and Croatian: from a vernacular form of the personal names Slovenian <i>Frančišek</i>, Croatian <i>Francisko</i> (from Latin <i>Franciscus</i>; see   Francis  ), derived from or influenced by German   Franz  . Compare   Frantz   2 and   Franck   4."],"variants":[{"name":"Franquez","meanings":["Hispanic (mainly Mexico): altered form, influenced by the Spanish patronymic suffix <i>-ez</i>, of Catalan <b>Franquès</b>, itself a derivative of   Franc   formed under the influence of <i>franquesa</i> ‘frankness’."]},{"name":"Frank","meanings":["German, Dutch, Scandinavian, Slovenian, Croatian, Czech, Slovak, Polish, Hungarian, and Jewish (Ashkenazic): ethnic or habitational name for someone from Franconia (German <i>Franken</i>), a region of southwestern Germany so called from its early settlement by the Franks, an ancient Germanic people who inhabited the lands around the River Rhine in Roman times. In the 6th–9th centuries, under leaders such as Clovis I (<i>c.</i> 466–511) and Charlemagne (742–814), the Franks established a substantial empire in western Europe, from which the country of France takes its name.","English (of Norman origin), Dutch, and German: from the personal name <i>Frank</i> (Norman French <i>Franco</i>, ancient Germanic <i>Franko</i>), in origin an ethnic name for a Frank, or from German <i>Franke</i> ‘Frank(ish), Franconian’ (compare 1 above). This also came to be used as an adjective meaning ‘free, open-hearted, generous’ (Middle English and Old French <i>franc</i> ‘free’, i.e. not a serf or slave), deriving from the fact that in Frankish Gaul only people of Frankish race enjoyed the status of fully free men. As a surname of German origin it is also found (in both possible meanings; see 1 above) in France (Alsace and Lorraine). Compare   Franc   and   Franck  ."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament: ‘God is gracious’.  See  <b>John</b> ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When John Franc was born about 1120, in Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Sir Humphrey Franc, was 24 and his mother, Mrs Humphrey Franc, was 22. He had at least 1 son with Wymark. He died before 1205."},"et":{"about 1120–before 1205":"umbes 1120–enne 1205","1120–1205":"1120–1205","1121–1205":"1121–1205","1141–Male":"1141–Surnud","1098–Male":"1098–Surnud","1100–Female":"1100–Surnud","Abt 1141":"umbes 1141","before 1205":"enne 1205","1205":"1205","1100":"1100","1121":"1121","1098":"1098","1120":"1120","1141":"1141","about 1120":"umbes 1120","Immersmere, Wiltshire, England":"Wiltshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Gloucestershire, England":"Gloucestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1120–before 1205":"noin 1120–ennen vuotta 1205","1120–1205":"1120–1205